metadata.name: String art generator #156
metadata.description:
Generative image with animation (1024x1024px) Vanilla JS

This project is a string-art simulator which weaves some patterns in different layouts to make beautiful compositions which can be played from the beginning.
The main features of this generative collection are the several Patterns and Layouts which combined make a huge amount of variations.

“Pattern” defined as the instructions that the thread has to follow to weave the result.
"Layout" defined as the setup of the nails on the board.

The thread is always continuous without interruptions.

Features:

Pattern (21)
Layout (10)
Palette (25)
Layout Mirror (None, Horizontal, Vertical)
ThreadType: (Silk, Wool)
ThreadThickness: (Regular, Thick)

Controls:

[P] Play. 
[R] Result.
[U] Undo. 
[N] Nails. Show/Hide the nails.

[S] Download snapshot (may be slow or unresponsive)

You can weave yourself
Click to change the thread color

This project is an homage to Mary Everest Boole who, more than 100 years ago, used string art to teach math to children.

metadata.name: RULES (for Elementary Cellular Automata) #429
metadata.description:
An important element of generative art is emergence. The most famous algorithm for this is probably Cellular Automata (CA).

However, numerous generative artists have created works using CA, which has lost its visual freshness and is like chewing gum that has lost its taste.

Although it is such a classic algorithm, adding my own little ideas to it and finding a new "flavor" is the reason why I code.

Here, the subject is 1D Elementary Cellular Automata, the simplest of all cellular automata. 1D Elementary Cellular Automata has 256 different rules, which change the shapes produced. This work aims to create more complex shapes by randomly selecting some of those rules and placing multiple of them on the screen.

The on/off of the CA cell is often likened to the behavior of living creatures.As of 2022, in the country where I live, prices are rising, wages are not increasing, and COVID-19 has not yet ended. I created this work with the image of people at the mercy of these various rules.

---

Screen click: Change rules
S key: Save png
L key: Show/hide grid

metadata.name: Win95 Larvas #52
metadata.description:
Welcome to the Win95 Larvas 🐛

Win95 Larvas is a collaboration with DOS Larvas, a CC0 project on the Tezos Blockchain. 

The Win95 Larvas are a 24x24 px remix of the original DOS Larvas released January 28 2022 on Fx Hash, using the 16 colors available in Windows95.


🐛 Size: 24x24 pixel
🐛 Format: .png
🐛 Colors 16
🐛 Layers: 9
🐛 Traits: 17
🐛 Glitch levels: 5

* Thanks to PureSpider for the great code.

metadata.name: ecologías - A #725
metadata.description:
ecologías - A

lines are a metaphor for the communication all species engage in. We as humans have a need to leave traces - stories - that others can read and learn from. What will be the traces machines want to leave? This piece employs sinusoidal signals drawn with lines as a simple metaphor for every trace and every language, for every message and every communication.

ecologías-A is an entity that is part of a broader ecology. Released on occasion of the show "Unbound - Ecology in the Age of Machines" at Unit London. The data generated by this entity is read by a different piece minted on Ethereum, creating a link between Tezos and Ethereum, a metaphor for an ecology of blockchains.

it shares a common element with two other works released on fxhash: ecologías B and ecologías C, all of them contributing data to aforementioned pieces.

read more at https://www.iillucid.com/ecologias

15% of primary sales are donated to institutions working towards improving biodiversity and environmental efforts.

Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro
CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/

Built on p5.js, glsl

append &pd=N (N a number) to the URL in live view to increase/decrease resolution
press s to save current image in current resolution
press z,x,g,b,n followed by +/- to increase/decrease, respectively, brightness, contrast, gamma, blur, noise
